{"key":"post-9122757","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9122757</id>\n<content>Here's the deal.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Mechanical hygrometers have a hair, often a human hair that expands and contracts due to humidity.&amp;nbsp; Any of you members with long hair knows this happens.&amp;nbsp; This hair pulls against a spring which is attached to the dial.&amp;nbsp; It's a simple instrument, but is only accurate through a narrow band, because a hair will only expand and contract so much, regardless of the change in humidity.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you're using the hygrometer in your house, or in a cigar humidor, use the salt method, since that is the range you want it to be accurate in.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you're using the hygrometer in a fruiting chamber, use the damp towel method, since you want your accuracy in the 95% range.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9134480</next>\n<prev>9122462</prev>\n<first>9121864</first>\n<last>9134480</last>\n<when>1224807805</when>\n<utime>10/24/08 03:23 AM</utime>\n</post>"}